analysis.info:
MEME (Mixed Effects Model of Evolution)
    estimates a site-wise synonymous (α) and a two-category mixture of non-synonymous
    (β-, with proportion p-, and β+ with proportion [1-p-]) rates, and
    uses a likelihood ratio test to determine if β+ > α at a site.
    The estimates aggregate information over a proportion of branches at a site,
    so the signal is derived from
    episodic diversification, which is a combination of strength of selection [effect size] and
    the proportion of the tree affected. A subset of branches can be selected
    for testing as well, in which case an additional (nuisance) parameter will be
    inferred -- the non-synonymous rate on branches NOT selected for testing. Multiple partitions within a NEXUS file are also supported
    for recombination - aware analysis.
analysis.citation: Detecting Individual Sites Subject to Episodic Diversifying Selection. _PLoS Genet_ 8(7): e1002764.
analysis.authors: Sergei L. Kosakovsky Pond, Steven Weaver
analysis.requirements: in-frame codon alignment and a phylogenetic tree

headers: Synonymous substitution rate at a site
Non-synonymous substitution rate at a site for the negative/neutral evolution component
Mixture distribution weight allocated to β<sup>-</sup>; loosely -- the proportion of the tree evolving neutrally or under negative selection
Non-synonymous substitution rate at a site for the positive/neutral evolution component
Mixture distribution weight allocated to β<sup>+</sup>; loosely -- the proportion of the tree evolving neutrally or under positive selection
Likelihood ratio test statistic for episodic diversification, i.e., p<sup>+</sup> > 0 <emph>and<emph> β<sup>+</sup> > α
Asymptotic p-value for episodic diversification, i.e., p<sup>+</sup> > 0 <emph>and<emph> β<sup>+</sup> > α
The (very approximate and rough) estimate of how many branches may have been under selection at this site, i.e., had an empirical Bayes factor of 100 or more for the β<sup>+</sup> rate
The total length of branches contributing to inference at this site, and used to scale dN-dS
